snippet.textDisplay:
I might like the idea of ARM-based gaming laptops, but most games right now are x86 and x86-64, so I wonder whether these can be easily emulated by the ARM-based emulators later on. But what I HATE about ARM machines is that the RAM and the storage are non-upgradeable (we've seen this with the current ARM-based Windows laptops, the M1-powered MacBooks and the iMac).

For some reason, I still like the Steam Deck though, and the potentially upgradeable storage is another cherry on top.

snippet.textDisplay:
The OLED switch definitely has a higher profit margin that the default switch. The switch already had a 100% profit margin at release, which  is in comparison to other consoles that are sold at a near loss or even a loss quite unusual. The hardware cost has decreased exponentially since then, yet the pricce stays the same or even rises. 
They could sell a switch at 150 USD and would still make a lot of profit. 
I am not saying that I really want a 150 dollar switch but considering what the product is actually worth, they really shouldn't sell it for more that 300 USD. 270 USD would probably a perfect price spot when it comes to what people are willing to pay and a massive profit margin. And considering that Nintendo can release any piece of low quality software as a game for 60+ bucks and people will buy it, the fact that more people would have a switch would almost very likely inccrease their overall profit margin.
